July 24--Albany International forecasts $16m loss
Union Leader staff
July 23. 2017 10:49PM
------
------
Albany International Corp. CEO Joseph Morone said the company is still on track to grow revenue this year 25 to 35 percent. (UNION LEADER FILE)
-- Albany International Corp. said it expects to record a second-quarter pre-tax charge of approximately $16 million associated with revisions in the estimated profitability of two contracts in its Rochester-based Albany Engineered Composites segment.
The charge, which will be recorded as part of the company's second-quarter financial results Aug. 1, is due to second-quarter 2017 downward revisions of estimated customer demand for the components manufactured by the composites segment related to the two contracts, the company said in a news release.
Albany International has a contract to manufacture composite components for the Rolls-Royce BR 725 engine, which powers Gulfstream's G-650 business jet. The contract obligates the company to supply the components for the life of the BR 725 program.
During the second quarter, Albany revised its estimate of the profitability of the contract and determined that an additional charge of approximately $10 million should be recorded as a provision for anticipated losses through the end of the program.
The charge is driven primarily by a reduction in the estimated future demand for these components, Albany said. The company previously recorded a charge of $14 million in the second quarter of 2015 for the program, including $11 million for the write-off of development costs for nonrecurring engineering and tooling, and $3 million for anticipated future losses.
Albany Engineered Composites's subsidiary, Albany Aerospace Composites LLC, has a contract to make composite struts for the Airbus A380, under which it is obligated to supply composite wing box struts through 2020 and floor beam struts through 2023.
During the second quarter, the company revised its estimate of the profitability of the contract and determined that a charge of approximately $6 million should be recorded as a provision for anticipated losses through contract completion. The revision is driven by a decrease in estimated demand for these components during the contract term, as well as by program inefficiencies.
"Unlike AEC's key growth and legacy programs, these two programs are exposed to the weakest segments in the commercial aerospace market -- business jets and super wide-bodies," CEO Joseph Morone said in a statement. "We do not consider either program to be strategic or material to AEC's growth prospects."
Combined revenue of the contracts for the first quarter was $1.1 million, the company said.
"We are meeting customer expectations in both programs, but because of very challenging legacy contracts, we lost money on both in Q1 2017 and had been expecting both programs to continue to lose money for several more years before turning profitable," Morone said.
Albany International is on track to grow revenue 25 to 35 percent this year, said Morone, citing what he noted in the company's first-quarter release. He said the company has the potential for revenue to reach $450 million to $500 million by 2020.
"While the recording of these projected future losses will obviously have a material impact on Q2 results, our outlook for AEC -- both in 2017 and beyond -- remains unchanged."
Business Rochester
___
